===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|threte}}, {{m|enm|thret}}, {{m|enm|thrat}}, {{m|enm|thræt}}, {{m|enm|threat}}, from {{inh|en|ang|þrēat|t=crowd, swarm, troop, army, press; pressure, trouble, calamity, oppression, force, violence, threat}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*þrautaz}}, closely tied to {{cog|gem-pro|*þrautą|t=displeasure, complaint, grievance, labour, toil}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*trewd-|t=to squeeze, push, press}}, whence also {{cog|gml|drōt|t=threat, menace, danger}}, {{cog|gmh|drōz|t=annoyance, disgust, horror, terror, fright}}, {{cog|is|þraut|t=struggle, labour, distress}}, {{cog|la|trūdō|t=push|pos=verb}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An [[expression]] of [[intent]] to [[injure]] or [[punish]] another.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Julius Caesar|4|3|text=There is no terror, Cassius, in your '''threats'''.}}
# An [[indication]] of [[potential]] or [[imminent]] [[danger]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=2013|month=May-June|author=[http://www.americanscientist.org/authors/detail/katrina-g-claw Katrina G. Claw]| title=[http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/2013/3/rapid-evolution-in-eggs-and-sperm Rapid Evolution in Eggs and Sperm]| volume=101| issue=3| magazine={{w|American Scientist}}| passage=Many genes with reproductive roles also have antibacterial and immune functions, which indicate that the '''threat''' of microbial attack on the sperm or egg may be a major influence on rapid evolution during reproduction.}}
# A person or object that is regarded as a danger; a [[menace]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=September 2, 2011|author=Phil McNulty|work=BBC| title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/14770875.stm Bulgaria 0-3 England]| passage=Rooney's United team-mate Chris Smalling was given his debut at right-back and was able to adjust to the international stage in relatively relaxed fashion as Bulgaria barely posed a '''threat''' of any consequence.}}

